izon tasks through next-token prediction and dense reward signals, yet exhibit substantial limitations in long-term reasoning and planning. This paper proposes that emotions evolved as a discrete tokenization mechanism solving the credit assignment problem in continuous action spaces. We formalize this hypothesis within a reinforcement learning framework, demonstrating how discrete emotional states enable Monte Carlo Tree Search-like planning over extended time horizons by circumventing the combinatorial explosion inherent in continuous action spaces. We present mathematical analysis of why discretization at the policy level is computationally necessary, supported by evidence from neuroscience and comparative biology. Our framework suggests that autonomous agents operating in continuous environments with sparse rewards may require analogous discrete tokenization mechanisms for effective long-term planning.<\/jats:p>","DOI":"10.2139\/ssrn.6069188","type":"posted-content","created":{"date-parts":[[2026,2,10]],"date-time":"2026-02-10T18:44:32Z","timestamp":1770749072000},"source":"Crossref","is-referenced-by-count":0,"title":["Emotions as Discrete Tokens for Credit Assignment"],"prefix":"10.2139","author":[{"given":"Ryuku","family":"Akahoshi","sequence":"first","affiliation":[]}],"member":"78","deposited":{"date-parts":[[2026,2,10]],"date-time":"2026-02-10T18:44:32Z","timestamp":1770749072000},"score":31.979595,"resource":{"primary":{"URL":"https:\/\/www.ssrn.com\/abstract=6069188"}},"issued":{"date-parts":[[2026]]},"references-count":0,"URL":"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.2139\/ssrn.6069188","published":{"date-parts":[[2026]]},"subtype":"preprint"},{"indexed":{"date-parts":[[2025,2,17]],"date-time":"2025-02-17T22:10:02Z","timestamp":1739830202366,"version":"3.37.3"},"reference-count":21,"publisher":"Elsevier BV","content-domain":{"domain":[],"crossmark-restriction":false},"short-container-title":["SSRN Journal"],"DOI":"10.2139\/ssrn.4324527","type":"journal-article","created"